							<hr width="100%" size="1" class="hrcolor" />
							<div class="post">The past two weeks I have been very busy. I apologize for only answering now to your question.<br /><br />I&#039;m not very sure about the definition of &quot;stall current&quot;, but the rated current of the motor I will be using is 18.7 A. And the driver I bought has a rated/peak current of 40A/60A, so I imagine I won&#039;t be facing the same problems you had with the controllers.<br /><br />By the way, I&#039;m curious about that last sentence &quot;because the spinning motor becomes a generator and you will be pushing current back into your controller without the diode!&quot;. Does that mean it will be possible for my kart to use regenerative breaking? Even though, I&#039;m going to use a driver with the specifications I already mentioned. If I buy a DC motor and he becomes a generator, and I also use a dissipation resistance with a super-capacitor.. Do you think I will be able to do that, or I&#039;m just saying nonsenses?</div>
